eries is brand-new; Epic and NVIDIA have active known-issue notes, and driver updates are the documented fix for exactly this \"UE5 crawls on RTX 50\" symptom.\n2. **Launch once and leave it for ~5 minutes without closing it.** With the cache cold (and after all my changes), the first play grinds while shaders compile, then should climb. Watch `stat fps` — if it rises over those minutes, that's the whole story.\n\nI can do two useful things right now if you want: **(a)** set up a *persistent* shader cache so it stops recompiling on every launch, or **(b)** revert all my render experiments back to a clean baseline. And if you just tell me the `stat fps` number after it's warmed up, we stop guessing entirely — that one number tells me whether this is shader-compile (fixable) or a driver bug (update/rollback).\n\nWhich do you want — (a), (b), or give me the `stat fps` number?\n\nSources: [Epic — RTX 50-series driver known issues](https://dev.epicgames.com/community/learning/knowledge-base/44lX/unreal-engine-tech-note-known-issues-with-nvidia-576-xx-drivers-on-rtx-50-series-gpus) · [UE5 shader/PSO stutter playbook](https://www.strayspark.studio/blog/ue5-shader-stutter-pso-precaching-playbook) · [Epic forums — Known issues with RTX 5000-series GPUs](https://forums.unrealengine.com/t/known-issues-with-rtx-5000-series-gpus/2619821)","background_tasks":[],"session_crons":[]}
